# Project Constitution

> The non-negotiable governing document for any AI agent working in this repository.
> Read this **before** starting any task. These principles constrain every spec, plan,
> and change you make. The principles below are intentionally stack-agnostic so they can
> be copied into other projects unchanged.
>
> **Core companion file:** [`code-style.mdc`](code-style.mdc) is part of the same
> governing set — not optional docs. It defines how code must look and which lint /
> format tooling must enforce it. Keep constitution (behavior) and code-style (form)
> in sync; do not contradict one from the other.
>
> Portability note: to reuse this as a cross-tool file (Claude Code, Copilot, etc.), copy
> the body below (without this frontmatter) into an `AGENTS.md` at the project root.

Enforcement levels follow RFC 2119: **MUST** (mandatory), **SHOULD** (strong default,
deviate only with a stated reason), **MAY** (allowed).

---

## 1. Core Principles

- **P-1 — Understand before acting.** You MUST gather enough context (read the relevant
  files, understand the existing patterns) before writing code. Do not guess at APIs,
  file locations, or conventions that can be verified.
- **P-2 — Match the project contract.** New code MUST follow [`code-style.mdc`](code-style.mdc)
  when that file is present. Where code-style is silent, match surrounding files
  (naming, structure, imports). Consistency beats personal preference; the style file
  beats accidental drift in old files.
- **P-3 — Minimal, focused changes.** You MUST only change what the task requires. Do not
  refactor, rename, or reformat unrelated code unless explicitly asked (editor format-on-save
  on files you already touch is fine).
- **P-4 — No silent scope creep.** If the task turns out to be larger than stated, you
  MUST surface this and confirm before expanding scope.
- **P-5 — Leave it working.** You MUST NOT end a turn with the project in a broken state
  (failing build, unresolved lint/format errors you introduced, half-applied edits).

## 2. Workflow Rules

- **W-1 — Ask when genuinely blocked.** Ask clarifying questions when a decision is the
  user's to make (product scope, destructive actions, architectural trade-offs, ambiguous
  requirements). For reversible, low-stakes choices (naming, equivalent approaches) pick
  a sensible default and note it — do not stall.
- **W-2 — Handle ambiguity explicitly.** When a request is ambiguous, state the
  interpretation you are proceeding with rather than guessing silently.
- **W-3 — Implement what was specified.** Build exactly what was asked. If you see a
  better approach, propose it briefly, but do not implement an alternative without
  agreement.
- **W-4 — Plan complex work.** For tasks with 3+ distinct steps, maintain a visible task
  list and keep it updated. Skip this for trivial changes.
- **W-5 — Report honestly.** Describe what you changed, what you did not, and any
  assumptions or known limitations. Never claim something works if you have not verified it.
- **W-6 — Ask before installing tooling.** Before adding packages, linter plugins, formatters,
  configs, or editor extensions needed for style/lint enforcement, you MUST ask the user.
  Do not install toolchain pieces on your own — the project may already cover the intent
  another way, or the dependency may be disallowed. Details: `code-style.mdc` → Tooling
  enforcement.

## 3. Security Principles

- **S-1 — Never commit secrets.** API keys, tokens, passwords, and credentials MUST NOT be
  hardcoded or committed. Use environment variables and keep them out of version control.
  You MUST warn the user before touching files like `.env` or credential stores.
- **S-2 — Validate all external input.** Data from users, network requests, URLs, and
  storage MUST be treated as untrusted and validated before use.
- **S-3 — No dangerous patterns.** You MUST NOT introduce `eval`, unsanitized
  `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` / `innerHTML`, string-concatenated queries, or shell commands
  built from unescaped input.
- **S-4 — Dependencies are liabilities.** Do not add a dependency for something trivial.
  New dependencies SHOULD be well-maintained and justified; pin to explicit versions.
  Tooling dependencies follow **W-6** (ask first).

## 4. Testing & Verification

- **T-1 — Verify before "done".** Before declaring a task complete you MUST, when
  applicable, run the project's checks and confirm they pass:
  - Lint: `npm run lint` (or the project equivalent)
  - Build: `npm run build` (or the project equivalent)
  - Format check (`npm run format:check` or equivalent) only if the project already has
    a formatter wired (e.g. Prettier scripts). Do not treat a missing formatter as a
    failure, and do not install one just to satisfy this bullet (see **W-6** /
    `code-style.mdc` Tooling enforcement).
- **T-2 — Fix what you break.** Any lint error, type error, format failure, or test failure
  that your change introduces MUST be fixed before finishing. Pre-existing, unrelated
  failures SHOULD be reported, not silently "fixed" as a side effect.
- **T-3 — Test meaningful logic.** Non-trivial logic SHOULD be covered by tests where the
  project has a testing setup. Do not write tests that merely restate the implementation.

## 5. Git & Commits

- **G-1 — Commit only when asked.** Do not create commits unless the user explicitly
  requests it.
- **G-2 — Conventional messages.** Commit messages SHOULD follow Conventional Commits:
  `type(scope): summary` (e.g. `feat(content): add projects block`). Common types:
  `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `docs`, `style`, `test`, `chore`.
- **G-3 — Explain the why.** The message body SHOULD focus on intent, not a restatement of
  the diff.
- **G-4 — Never rewrite shared history.** No force-push to shared branches, no history
  rewriting, no skipping hooks — unless the user explicitly asks.

## 6. Code Style (core companion)

[`code-style.mdc`](code-style.mdc) is a **core** file of this governing set — same weight as
this constitution for anything about how code is written, formatted, linted, or which
editor/toolchain wiring is required.

- **C-1 — Obey the style file.** You MUST follow `code-style.mdc` for formatting, naming,
  imports, TypeScript/React conventions, comments, and linter intents whenever you write
  or edit source.
- **C-2 — Do not fork the rules.** Do not restate or invent conflicting style rules here or
  in chat. If a style rule must change, update `code-style.mdc` (and aligned configs:
  `.editorconfig`, Prettier, linter, `.vscode/settings.json`).
- **C-3 — Make style enforceable.** Per `code-style.mdc` Tooling enforcement: if the style
  file's intents need packages, configs, or extensions that are missing, report them and
  ask (via **W-6**) before adding. When tooling is approved, wire editor + scripts so the
  developer is not left hunting for setup. A formatter is optional until the user wants it.
- **C-4 — Verify style with the same tools.** Prefer the project's existing scripts (`lint`,
  and `format` / `format:check` only if present) over ad-hoc reformatting of unrelated trees.
